Using base of 300k per annum, that alone gets Tesla almost to 700k in the two years. With the aggressive scaling up the company is moving towards, it is likely to get past 1.2M cumulative over the two year period. Although softer gas pricing may slow addition of other companies' EV products, Tesla has such a strong image and customer base that touts the cars that this will not seriously impact its sales.

Projecting a delivery rate at current levels comes in under 700,000 vehicles being delivered to customers in 2021 and 2022. I do not anticipate that Tesla will be able to exceed the number of vehicles delivered in Q1 of 2020 due to many economic factors. Weighing external factors such as market saturation effects (the early adopters of the product have been fulfilled, so Tesla will need to convert conventional vehicle buyers to be buyers of their products), job insecurity and unemployment effects (individuals stop purchasing new vehicles in periods of economic uncertainty) I do not foresee demand increasing in 2021 and 2022, and the possibility of dropping by as much as 20%. In addition, there may be internal operation issues for Tesla, including production bandwidth to produce more than 700,000 vehicles as their production in 2019 was 367,500 , and Tesla has not yet added an assembly plant to its facilities to be able to increase production. While Tesla is in negotiations to add production plants in Texas, to have those plants up and producing in order to exceed the 700,000 mark is unlikely in the timeframe being discussed.
